16.body: There is an official CycloneDX cargo subcommand to generate a SBOM from a Rust project source, cargo-cyclonedx cargo cyclonedx --all --format json --manifest-path Cargo.toml It can handle workspaces, and produces a json or XML file. To aggregate several files, validate or sign them, you can use the cyclonedx-cli . cyclonedx merge --input-files *.json --output-file myprogram.cdx.json spdx cargo auditable rust version in binary trivy, other tooling... warning not everything is visible: embedded c/c++ deps not visible, etc.

17.body: In this section, we will see what we can do to track known vulnerabilities in Rust programs. It won't cover generic deployment security as there are numerous options (containers, Windows msi/exe installers, Linux rpm/dpkg/etc. packages, etc.) but you should make sure you can verify that deployed artifacts' source and integrity (various artifact signature mechanism can help).
17.title: Running in production

18.body:
cargo audit has some capacities to audit Rust binaries for known vulnerabilities in their dependencies. It has two operation modes in this context: Audit for known vulnerabilities in the dependency list embedded by cargo-auditable. Audit for known vulnerabilities in a dependency list extracted from panic messages. This is incomplete as not all crates include panics Depending on the compilation options, panic messages may not be available You can also use other tools like trivy which is able to look for known vulnerabilities in Rust binaries by using the same dependency list built by cargo-auditable. $ trivy image --security-checks vuln docker-image

2.body: This guide is aimed at both developers working on Rust programs for end-users and libraries developers. It focuses on currently available tooling for the Rust ecosystem, but also mentions more general advice or tooling. It has a hands-on focus and tries to provide actionnable items whenever possible. It will also mention the current limitations and missing parts. It builds upon existing resources, like llogiq's blog post .
2.title: About this guide

3.body: cargo makes it really easy to use dependencies, so the Rust ecosystem tends to use a lot of them. This comes with security risks, and we'll see how we can mitigate them.
